title: Peptide workflow with DaparToolshed
text: DaparToolshed package analyzing quantitative data label-free bottom-proteomics experiments. uses MultiAssayExperiment, SummarizedExperiment QFeatures data structures (Gatto Vanderaa (2025)). Starting table abundance values associated metdata, DaparToolshed proposes functions build complete statistical analysis workflow selection differentially expressed proteins contrasted conditions. DaparToolshed makes possible import data different levels: precursor, peptide protein, requiring specific processing. vignette describes complete precursor- peptide-level workflow. package used Prostar2 package, provides user-friendly graphical interfaces, programming skill required achieve data analysis.

title: Peptide workflow with DaparToolshed
text: normalization step reduces biases introduced preliminary stage, make samples comparable. Though full batch effect correction method (can required depending experimental design), can limit simple batch effects. step, peptide abundances essentially rescaled samples conditions conditions. Several algorithms implemented DaparToolshed list available methods can accessed using normalizeMethods() : methods proposed acts described : GlobalQuantileAlignment : Aligns quantiles intensity distributions across samples. (method used cautiously, imposes high-impact normalization. Broadly speaking, abundances replaced order statistics). SumByColumns : Normalizes abundance value total abundance corresponding sample. Un-logged intensities used processing. method assumes total amount biological material equal samples . QuantileCentering : Aligns intensity distributions specific quantile, e.g., median lower quantile, either across samples within condition. MeanCentering : Aligns intensity distributions means, either across samples within condition. Optionally, unit variance can enforced. LOESS : Applies cyclic LOESS normalization, either across samples within condition. intensity values normalized means local regression model difference intensities function median intensity value (Cleveland (1979)) (see Smyth (2005) implementation details). vsn : Applies Variance Stabilization Normalization method, either across samples within condition (Huber et al. (2002)). normalizeFunction() function allows normalize data using methods described create new assay normalized data. parameters defined depend chosen method. type argument allows indicate whether method applied entire dataset ("overall") whether condition normalized independently ("within conditions"). compareNormalizationD_HC() function provides way visually compare quantitative data normalization. plot shows influence normalization method.
code: #list of available methods normalizeMethods() ## [1] "GlobalQuantileAlignment" "SumByColumns"            ## [3] "QuantileCentering"       "MeanCentering"           ## [5] "LOESS"                   "vsn" obj <- normalizeFunction(obj,                          method = "MeanCentering",                          scaling = TRUE,                          type = "overall")  obj ## An instance of class QFeatures (type: bulk) with 4 sets: ##  ##  [1] original: SummarizedExperiment with 500 rows and 6 columns  ##  [2] logAssay: SummarizedExperiment with 500 rows and 6 columns  ##  [3] Filtered: SummarizedExperiment with 480 rows and 6 columns  ##  [4] Normalization: SummarizedExperiment with 480 rows and 6 columns obj1 <- obj[[length(obj)]] obj2 <- obj[[length(obj)-1]] protId <- DaparToolshed::idcol(obj1)  .n <- floor(0.02 * nrow(obj1)) .subset <- seq(nrow(obj1))  compareNormalizationD_HC(   qDataBefore = SummarizedExperiment::assay(obj1),   qDataAfter = SummarizedExperiment::assay(obj2),   keyId = SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj1)[, protId],   conds = DaparToolshed::design.qf(obj)$Condition,   n = .n,   subset.view = .subset )

code: #remove pushed p-values pushedpval_ind <- which(pval > 1) pval_nopush <- pval[-pushedpval_ind]   #calibration plot with all methods  calibration_all <- wrapperCalibrationPlot(vPVal = pval_nopush,                                            pi0Method  = "ALL") calibration_all$pi0 ##   pi0.Storey.Spline pi0.Storey.Boot pi0.Jiang pi0.Histo pi0.Langaas pi0.Pounds ## 1         0.6383234       0.6035503 0.6679852 0.6973795   0.6122122  0.7489547 ##     pi0.ABH  pi0.SLIM ## 1 0.9467456 0.8832706 #chosen pi0 pi0 <- 1   #calibration plot with chosen method wrapperCalibrationPlot(vPVal = pval_nopush,                         pi0Method  = pi0) ## $pi0 ## [1] 1 ##  ## $h1.concentration ## [1] 0 ##  ## $unif.under ## [1] 0.006418716 #histogram of p-values density histPValue_HC(pval_nopush,               bins = 50,               pi0 = pi0 ) #push to 1 proteins with logFC under threshold pval_pushfc <- pval pval_logfc_inf_ind <- which(abs(res_pval_FC$logFC) < Foldchange_thlogFC) pval_logfc_inf_ind <- setdiff(pval_logfc_inf_ind, pushedpval_ind) pval_pushfc[pval_logfc_inf_ind] <- 1  #remove pushed p-values pval_pushfc <- pval_pushfc[-pushedpval_ind]    #calculate adjusted p-values adjusted_pvalues <- diffAnaComputeAdjustedPValues(   pval_pushfc,   pi0) ## Procedure of Benjamini-Hochberg is used. pi0 is fixed to 1. adjusted_pvalues_comp <- unlist(res_pval_FC$P_Value) adjusted_pvalues_comp[-pushedpval_ind] <- adjusted_pvalues

title: Peptide workflow with DaparToolshed
text: final step FDR control, aims limit proportion false positives among proteins identified differentially abundant. p-value threshold first defined select proteins deemed differentially abundant. protein p-value threshold retained. associated FDR level provided, based p-value adjustment procedure. expected number false discoveries can estimated multiplying FDR number significant proteins. FDR percentage-based measure, becomes difficult interpret expected number falsely discovered proteins falls 1, corresponds strictly less one expected false discovery. likely happen small datasets. However, FDR becomes meaningless invalidate proteomics experiment . means FDR used cautiously. diffAnaVolcanoplot_rCharts() function provides volcano plot visualize differentially abundant proteins according logFC p-value thresholds. requires data.frame containing logFC, log-transformed p-values, protein index, additional information displayed tooltip hovering point plot. FDR threshold corresponds horizontal dashed line, logFC threshold vertical dashed line. new assay can created keep values interest, p-values, logFCs, differential non-differential status protein. allows keep data organized single object reuse later necessary processing visualization.
code:
#define p-value threshold pval_threshold <- 0.01 FDRcontrol_thpval <- -log10(pval_threshold)   #get FDR pval[pushedpval_ind] <- 1 logpval <- -log10(pval) logpval_thpval_ind <- which(logpval >= FDRcontrol_thpval) logpval_thpval_ind <- setdiff(logpval_thpval_ind, pval_logfc_inf_ind) fdr <- diffAnaComputeFDR(adjusted_pvalues_comp[logpval_thpval_ind])   #determine differentially abundant proteins isDifferential <- is.differential(pvalue = pval,                                  logFC = res_pval_FC$logFC,                                  thpvalue = FDRcontrol_thpval,                                  thlogFC = Foldchange_thlogFC) NbSignificant <- length(which(isDifferential == 1))  cat("pvalue threshold : ", pval_threshold, "
",     "logpvalue threshold : ", FDRcontrol_thpval, "
",     "FDR : ", round(100*fdr, 2), "%
",     "Number significant proteins : ", NbSignificant, "
",     "Number of expected false discovery : ", fdr*NbSignificant, "
") ## pvalue threshold :  0.01  ##  logpvalue threshold :  2  ##  FDR :  16.75 % ##  Number significant proteins :  19  ##  Number of expected false discovery :  3.18342 #create dataframe for volcano plot df <- data.frame(   x = unlist(res_pval_FC$logFC),   y = logpval,   index = as.character(rownames(obj[[length(obj)]]))   ) tooltip <- "proteinId" df <- cbind(df, SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj[[length(obj)]])[, tooltip, drop = FALSE]) colnames(df) <- gsub(".", "_", colnames(df), fixed = TRUE) if (ncol(df) > 3) {   colnames(df)[4:ncol(df)] <- paste0("tooltip_",                                       colnames(df)[4:ncol(df)]) } cond <- unique(design.qf(obj)$Condition)   #volcano plot diffAnaVolcanoplot_rCharts(   df,   th_pval = FDRcontrol_thpval,   th_logfc = Foldchange_thlogFC,   conditions = cond ) #create new assay with all values of interest obj <- QFeatures::addAssay(obj, obj[[length(obj)]], 'DifferentialAnalysis') SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj[[length(obj)]])$pval <- unlist(res_pval_FC$P_Value) SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj[[length(obj)]])$logpval <- logpval SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj[[length(obj)]])$logFC <- unlist(res_pval_FC$logFC)  SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj[[length(obj)]])$adjusted_pval <- adjusted_pvalues_comp  SummarizedExperiment::rowData(obj[[length(obj)]])$isDifferential <- isDifferential  obj ## An instance of class QFeatures (type: bulk) with 8 sets: ##  ##  [1] original: SummarizedExperiment with 500 rows and 6 columns  ##  [2] logAssay: SummarizedExperiment with 500 rows and 6 columns  ##  [3] Filtered: SummarizedExperiment with 480 rows and 6 columns  ##  ... ##  [6] aggregated: SummarizedExperiment with 378 rows and 6 columns  ##  [7] FilterProt: SummarizedExperiment with 357 rows and 6 columns  ##  [8] DifferentialAnalysis: SummarizedExperiment with 357 rows and 6 columns

code: data(feat1, package = 'QFeatures') ## ---------------------------------------- ## Creating function filters ## ----------------------------------------  #FunctionFilter('FUN', #               param1 = 'value_of_param1', #               param2 = 'value_of_param2')  FunctionFilter('qMetacellWholeLine',                cmd = 'delete',                pattern = 'imputed POV') #> An object of class "FunctionFilter" #> Slot "name": #> [1] "qMetacellWholeLine" #>  #> Slot "params": #> $cmd #> [1] "delete" #>  #> $pattern #> [1] "imputed POV" #>  #>   ## ---------------------------------------------------------------- ## Filter the last assay to keep only specific peptides. This filter ## only applies on peptide dataset. ## ----------------------------------------------------------------  spec.filter <- FunctionFilter('specPeptides', list()) ## using a user-defined character filter filterFeaturesOneSE(feat1, list(FunctionFilter('specPeptides', list()))) #> An instance of class QFeatures (type: bulk) with 1 set: #>  #>  [1] psms: SummarizedExperiment with 10 rows and 2 columns    ## ---------------------------------------------------------------- ## Filter the last assay to keep only specific peptides and topn  ## peptides. The two filters are run sequentially. ## ----------------------------------------------------------------  lst.filters <- list(FunctionFilter('specPeptides', list())) lst.filters <- append(lst.filters, FunctionFilter('topnPeptides', fun = 'rowSums', top = 2)) filterFeaturesOneSE(feat1, lst.filters) #> An instance of class QFeatures (type: bulk) with 1 set: #>  #>  [1] psms: SummarizedExperiment with 10 rows and 2 columns   ## ---------------------------------------------------------------- ## Filter the last assay to delete peptides where, in at least one  ## condition, there is less than 80% of samples marked as 'imputed POV' ## ----------------------------------------------------------------  filter <- FunctionFilter('qMetacellOnConditions', cmd = 'delete', mode = 'AtLeastOneCond', pattern = 'imputed POV', conds = SummarizedExperiment::colData(feat1)$Condition, percent = TRUE, th = 0.8, operator = '<')   filterFeaturesOneSE(feat1, filter) #> An instance of class QFeatures (type: bulk) with 1 set: #>  #>  [1] psms: SummarizedExperiment with 10 rows and 2 columns

code: data(subR25prot) obj <- subR25prot[[2]] grp <- design.qf(subR25prot)$Condition lapala <- findMECBlock(obj, grp) na.type = c("Missing POV", "Missing MEC") obj.imp.pov <- wrapper.impute.detQuant(obj, na.type = na.type) obj.imp.pov <- reIntroduceMEC(obj, grp, lapala)  obj.imp.pov <- wrapper.impute.KNN(obj, grp, 3) #> Warning: 2 rows with more than 99 % entries missing; #>  mean imputation used for these rows #> Warning: 2 rows with more than 99 % entries missing; #>  mean imputation used for these rows  obj.imp.pov <- wrapper.impute.fixedValue(obj, grp, 0.001, na.type = "Missing POV") obj.imp.mec <- wrapper.impute.fixedValue(obj, grp, 0.001, na.type = "Missing MEC") obj.imp.na <- wrapper.impute.fixedValue( obj, grp, 0.001,  na.type = c("Missing MEC", "Missing POV"))  obj.imp.pov <- wrapper.impute.pa(obj, grp)  qdata <- SummarizedExperiment::assay(obj) quant <- getQuantile4Imp(qdata)
